{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14238"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.32,0.01,0.49,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41820"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"959"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"3747"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33227"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing left-sided abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and not associated with any gastrointestinal or urinary tract symptoms. He has a medical history of an episode of diverticulitis one year ago, hypertension, and pulmonary embolism. His regular medications include atorvastatin, perindopril, and warfarin. Last week, he was started on a course of antibiotics for a chest infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but not acutely unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 132/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with no guarding, localised tenderness or palpable masses. There is no evidence of bruising on the abdominal wall. Bowel sounds are present and normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Images 1 and 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal cell carcinoma","Psoas abscess","Pancreatitis","Retroperitoneal haematoma","Lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large left-sided retroperitoneal mass, which in the context of this patient\u0027s history and presentation, is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eretroperitoneal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E. This diagnosis is supported by several factors: the patient\u0027s age, use of warfarin, recent antibiotic use, and the CT appearance of a heterogeneous mass in the retroperitoneal space. The mass extends from the level of the left kidney inferiorly into the pelvis. The mass appears to displace adjacent structures but does not invade them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetroperitoneal haemorrhage is a rare but serious complication of anticoagulation therapy, particularly in elderly patients. The recent course of antibiotics likely potentiated the effect of warfarin, increasing the risk of bleeding. The constant abdominal pain without other associated symptoms is typical of a retroperitoneal bleed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a solid, enhancing mass arising from the kidney itself. While it can sometimes be quite large at presentation, the acute onset of symptoms and the patient\u0027s anticoagulation status make this diagnosis less likely. Additionally, renal cell carcinoma would typically show some degree of enhancement on CT, which is not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E could present with similar symptoms, but would typically be associated with fever, more localised tenderness, and possibly a history of back pain. On CT, it would appear as a more well-defined, fluid-filled collection, often with rim enhancement. The patient\u0027s normal temperature and lack of localised tenderness argue against this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, often associated with nausea and vomiting. The CT appearance would show inflammation of the pancreas, possibly with peripancreatic fluid collections, rather than a discrete retroperitoneal mass. The lack of typical symptoms and the CT appearance make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can certainly present as a retroperitoneal mass, but it would typically be more homogeneous in appearance on CT and would not have such an acute onset. Lymphoma is also often associated with systemic symptoms such as fever, night sweats, and weight loss, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of the patient\u0027s anticoagulation status, recent antibiotic use, clinical presentation, and CT findings strongly support the diagnosis of a retroperitoneal haematoma. Management would typically involve reversal of anticoagulation, close monitoring, and possibly surgical intervention if the bleeding is ongoing or if there are signs of compression of adjacent structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retroperitoneal haemorrhage is a rare but serious complication of anticoagulation therapy, particularly in elderly patients.","Antibiotic use can potentiate the effect of warfarin, increasing the risk of bleeding complications.","CT imaging is the gold standard for diagnosing retroperitoneal haemorrhage."],"references":["Kasotakis G. Retroperitoneal and Rectus Sheath Hematomas. Surg Clin N Am 94 2014; 71\u201376. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24267499/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41820"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21037"},{"type":"media","id":"21038"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21037"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZxKCC76x8sBZkSYgfrS73f9H9UWjX2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZxKCC76x8sBZkSYgfrS73f9H9UWjX2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":890,"height":647}},{"type":"media","id":"21038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21038"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QLT6blNR3p85vRx1wx4ywMhHxy1M0i.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QLT6blNR3p85vRx1wx4ywMhHxy1M0i.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":690,"height":822}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41820"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T21:40:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T21:41:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6925"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null